INFLUENZA PANDEMIC, 1918: ARCHEOLOGY (03)
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Influenza pandemic, 1918: archeology 971007174128
Influenza pandemic, 1918: archeology (02) 971013210158

[Here are two additional comments on the special virulence of the 1918
influenza pandemic, and then I think I will cut the thread. -Mod. ES
[1
Date: Wed, 15 Oct 1997 03:06:51 -0400 (EDT)
From: Jonathan Mayer <jmayer@hsph.harvard.edu>

The conventional explanation for why the pandemic struck the 20-40 year old
age group has been that World War I was in full force, and the density of
living quarters were ideal for transmission among soldiers--people in
this age group. However, this is not completely satisfactory, since it
also struck people in this age group who were not in the military. Another
explanation is that there was a pandemic in 1889 that is putatively thought
to have been the same strain as 1918-19. However, that would not explain
the attack rates in people over 30. It remains a mystery. The most
accessible work on this is Alfred Crosby's book [Dr. Mayer didn't have the
exact reference available at the moment, but it should be easy to find
-Mod. ES.
--
Jonathan D. Mayer, Ph.D.
