[2
Date: October 15, 1997
From: Martin Hugh-Jones, Moderator, ProMED-mail

You might keep in mind in regard to the elderly being left out and the
young adults over-represented [during the 1918 influenza pandemic, that
this is exactly the pattern that would be expected if there had been a
previous pandemic (overt or covert) of a related influenza virus, say
25-30 years before, that had provided cross protection, or even of a more
closely related flu virus (i.e. the same virus coming round again).
With the development and expansive use of railways and fast steam-driven
ships, the extent of long-distance travel had rocketed in the decades prior
to 1918. Therefore late 19th Century pandemics of flu cannot be ruled out.
--
Martin Hugh-Jones
ProMED-mail
